&lt;p&gt;I believe that bicyclo[2.2.1]heptane does not react in the way depicted in the question as opposed to bicyclo[3.3.1]nonane because of of the number of carbons that make up the ring structure. In fact, carbonium ions are more easily formed&nbsp;at bridgehead positions when a structure&nbsp;can have a planar-like geometry&nbsp;at that position. This is rather achieved in larger ring systems as is observed in the case of bicyclo[3.3.1]nonane. If such geometric conditions are not met, then the energy will increase and the compound will become less stable.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Thus, due to the bigger ring structure in reaction A, planar-like geometry at the bridgehead position can be obtained and the product of the reaction is more stable.&lt;/p&gt;

